The "blocate" command can be used like the "locate" command,
except it loops over all mlocate.*.db files you have
in this directory.

To make new ones, use something like

  sudo ./do_updatedb u=/media/teuben/raid500_14                           d=raid500_14
  sudo ./do_updatedb u=/media/teuben/21a68621-1ae1-4211-8513-f651e44f7f42 d=1TB-1
  sudo ./do_updatedb u=/media/teuben/Backup                               d=1TB-2
  sudo ./do_updatedb u=/media/teuben/25d99aef-27ad-4747-802d-9ec0832c39bb d=1TB-3

See also:
  https://trendoceans.com/locate-command-usage-in-linux/
  https://github.com/Aetf/plocate
  ~/teunix/bin/blocate

## mlocate.db(5)

A mlocate database starts with a file header: 8 bytes for a magic
number ("\0mlocate" like a C literal), 4 bytes for the configuration
block size in big endian, 1 byte for file format version (0), 1 byte
for the 'require visibility' flag (0 or 1), 2 bytes padding, and a
SMNUL-terminated path name of the root of the database.

00000000  00 6d 6c 6f 63 61 74 65  00 00 01 27 00 01 00 00  |.mlocate...'....|
                                   <4 bytes -> fv rv <pad>
00000000  00 6d 6c 6f 63 61 74 65  00 00 00 27 00 01 00 00  |.mlocate...'....|
00000000  00 6d 6c 6f 63 61 74 65  00 00 00 27 00 01 00 00  |.mlocate...'....|
00000000  00 6d 6c 6f 63 61 74 65  00 00 01 27 00 00 00 00  |.mlocate...'....|


The command

     plocate-build  mlocate.home640.db  plocate.home640.db

should (after fixing the visibility flag)

     locate -d plocate.home640.db /

still doesntt work

# not working
00000000  00 70 6c 6f 63 61 74 65  01 00 00 00 03 25 01 00  |.plocate.....%..|
# working
00000000  00 70 6c 6f 63 61 74 65  01 00 00 00 7f 7b 01 00  |.plocate.....{..|
